<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/opinion <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/opinion" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 3 日星期四 23:10:31 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Trump’s Jan. 6 Trial: We Owe It to History]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>与此同时，亨特·拜登的法律问题对美国中产阶级选民来说变得更加重要。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128382857298148"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128382857298148"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/peggy-noonan"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BS053_noonan_AM_20180912120458.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/peggy-noonan" itemprop="url" rel="author">佩吉·努南</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 6:48 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-jan-6-trial-we-owe-it-to-history-indictment-president-election-crime-washington-5e643a14"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829525?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">唐纳德·特朗普 (Donald Trump) 于 8 月 3 日抵达弗吉尼亚州阿灵顿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历克斯·布兰登/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>现已因 2021 年 1 月 6 日前后采取的行动受到刑​​事指控。他被指控策划颠覆宪法，意图在 2020 年总统选举失败后保留权力。</p><p>无论起诉书的政治性如何发展，案件提交到被指控犯罪的发生地华盛顿的法庭和陪审团是正确和恰当的。这既重申了法治的首要地位，又提醒我们宪政共和国是如何运作的：如果行政部门滥用权力，司法部门将做出裁决。</p><p>我们把这归功于历史。正式地、最终地讲到故事的结尾。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>有人认为，起诉书针对的是特朗普的想法，这令人不安：他相信自己所说的有关选举被盗的言论，还是在撒谎？这说明了意图。他的辩护者辩称他相信这一点，即使他不相信，他仍然在第一修正案的保护下运作。与他关系疏远的司法部长威廉·巴尔(William Barr)不同意，他告诉美国有线电视新闻网(CNN)：“他可以说任何他想说的话，他甚至可以撒谎。 。 。 。但这并不能保护你免于陷入阴谋。”</p><p>特朗普先生的看法让我觉得这个问题离题了。根据长期的观察，他并不“相信”；他本质上不是一个信徒。他长期以来的运作方法是战略性地部署概念和方法，看看什么有效。换句话说，他编造了一些东西，如果它飞了就坚持下去，如果飞不起来就扔掉它，然后继续“相信”其他东西。</p><p>但总而言之，这个故事的严重性意味着必须提起刑事指控，以及接下来的一切——提审、审前动议、审判、出示证据、总结、判决、量刑，如果他被定罪。其他考虑因素（它们是真实存在的）都是次要的。</p><p>起诉的时机是否不当？是的，在一个总统周期中，虽然亨特·拜登的故事达到了一个新的水平，但已经过去了很多时间。起诉书公布时，普通人并不像媒体想象的那样激动不已。感觉就像已经发生了一些事情。我们参加了去年 1 月 6 日特别委员会的听证会，看到了总统周围人士的所有戏剧性证词。我们读过书，看过纪录片。这件事不是<em>已经</em>告上法庭了吗？</p><p>在这一点上，“至少现在我们都会弄清楚我们的立场”这一点不会有任何澄清的意义。我们都知道我们的立场。对于前总统的支持者来说，这看起来像是腐败的、民主党控制的司法部在政治上的杀伤力，而司法部永远不会停止追捕特朗普。如果他倒地身亡，他们就会追究他的死因。</p><p>然而：这一切可能发生得很晚，但它必须发生。</p><p>我提到了亨特·拜登，在起诉书之前，他的案件一直是本专栏的主题。这个故事正在发生一些事情，一些重大的转变正在发生。在过去一个月左右的时间里，它以新的方式取得了突破。</p><p>这个故事变得更加真实、更加充实，尤其是对于中间的人来说。在对亨特故事的旧理解中，一个吸毒的性瘾君子在一台丢失的笔记本电脑上记录了他的冒险经历。尴尬，但每个家庭都有。新兴的猎人故事本质上是不同的。是这样的：这个家伙实际上很擅长某件事，是一个严重的影响力贩子和接线员，所以他从来没有被抓住。</p><p>一些右翼人士一直这么认为。我认为现在它正在被政治立场和参与度较低的人们所接受和观看。这个故事已经呈现出不同程度的肮脏。它开始看起来不再像家庭忠诚，而是一种赋能，不仅是赋能，而且这样做是为了寻求利润。</p><p> 5 月和 7 月底，两名国税局举报人，特别监察员加里·沙普利 (Gary Shapley) 和特别探员约瑟夫·齐格勒 (Joseph Ziegler)，在国会作证时将自己的职业生涯置于危险之中。这是可信的；他们令人印象深刻。他们表示，美国国税局阻碍了对亨特·拜登收入及其来源（包括海外商业交易）的调查。齐格勒表示，司法部官员的调查“有限且边缘化”。沙普利告诉哥伦比亚广播公司新闻，他追踪涉及“爸爸”或“大人物”（亨特对他父亲的委婉说法）的资金踪迹的努力遭到了司法部的阻止。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>了解更多声明</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-i-wish-oppenheimer-had-said-nuclear-war-weapons-movie-blockbuster-military-john-hersey-c311a3c3?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">我希望“奥本海默”说的话</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 27 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-talent-strikes-back-hollywood-union-writers-actors-tv-movie-industry-6bf4e49f?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">人才反击</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 20 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-artificial-intelligence-ukraine-war-russia-putin-china-brooke-astor-c6a9a1fa?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">夏日天空中的精灵</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 13 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>同样是在七月下旬，在特拉华州威尔明顿的联邦法院，认罪协议失败了。它涉及针对亨特的税收和持有枪支指控。法官</p>玛丽莲·诺雷卡 (Maryellen Noreika) 告诉联邦检察官和辩护律师回去再试一次，这笔交易看起来并不正常，而且她也没有在那里“盖上橡皮图章”。<p></p><p>随后，亨特的商业伙伴、据说是亨特最好的朋友德文·阿彻 (Devon Archer) 在国会作证。阿彻在众议院监督委员会的闭门证词中表示，作为副总统，乔·拜登参加了与乌克兰能源公司布里斯马公司代表的电话交谈，阿彻和亨特·拜登是该公司的董事会成员。阿彻先生的完整证词于周四公布。他证实，副总统参加了亨特的外国商业伙伴的一次晚宴，不久之后，350 万美元就汇入了亨特的一个商业实体。</p><p>至少可以说，这是不体面的。</p><p>另一件突破性的事情是：当谈到亨特·拜登时，人们使用诸如“总统的麻烦儿子”之类的语言。总给人一种他还是个孩子的感觉，他小时候就不幸失去了母亲，作为年幼、不那么令人印象深刻的儿子，他的青春期充满了麻烦。</p><p>亨特·拜登今年 53 岁。在这个年纪，有些人已经是祖父了。他在与乌克兰和中国公司做生意时，不再是一个任性的25岁年轻人，而是一个中年男子。成年人对自己的行为完全负责的年龄。</p><p>这是故事中意想不到的政治转折。总统对美国中产阶级的名片一直是“中产阶级乔”，来自斯克兰顿的顾家男人，一个有一定尊严的普通人，正如他所说，靠工资生活，并且经历过个人悲剧。不管是否正确，这就是他的政治立场，而且这对他很有好处。但亨特的故事有可能将他父亲的公众声誉转移到克林顿的领域——人们感觉事情都是粗略地谋求私利，对金钱太感兴趣。希拉里·克林顿 (Hillary Clinton) 在 2016 年落败，就是因为她在这方面的政治声誉。</p><p>我怀疑亨特问题将在选举中持续存在并不断扩大。这是一个人们可以理解的故事——一个没出息的儿子通过兜售影响力、兜售名誉、兜售权势等方式来谋取金钱。涉及多少钱？它去哪儿了？</p><p>这不是什么主义。这些都是合理的问题。</p><p>七年来，民主党人因不愿谈论唐纳德·特朗普而赢得了共和党官员的青睐。为什么他们对亨特不承认任何事情，甚至不承认人们的看法是不好的？老实说，他们为什么不感到困扰呢？</p><p>主流媒体还有工作要做。这是一个故事。让碎片落到该落的地方。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-jan-6-trial-we-owe-it-to-history-indictment-president-election-crime-washington-5e643a14</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-jan-6-trial-we-owe-it-to-history-indictment-president-election-crime-washington-5e643a14<author><![CDATA[Peggy Noonan]]></author><category>带电</category><category>犯罪</category><category>总统</category><category>选举</category><category>起诉书</category><category>法庭</category><category>华盛顿</category><category>选举被盗</category><category>第一修正案</category><category>捍卫者</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Turmoil in Northern Africa]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>尼日尔政变和俄罗斯干预造成的危害不会只留在萨赫勒地区。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590123961213212260"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590123961213212260"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 6:47（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-sahel-africa-mohamed-bazoum-state-department-c627cbc5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829604?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 30 日，在尼日尔尼亚美举行的抗议活动中，人们在国民议会大楼外展示俄罗斯和尼日尔国旗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：issifou djibo/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>非洲萨赫勒地区政治不稳定和恐怖主义长期困扰，尼日尔不断发生的政变更是雪上加霜。美国本周从其大使馆撤离了一些人员，其影响可能会蔓延到其他大陆。</p><p>尼日尔总统卫队上周拘留了民选总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆，卫队领导人阿卜杜拉赫马内·奇亚尼将军宣布自己为国家元首。巴祖姆尚未辞职，美国国务院发言人周一描述了“持续的、不稳定的局势”，“尚不清楚”政变是否会成功。</p><p>这场骚乱威胁到基地组织和伊斯兰国附属组织博科圣地和穆斯林努斯拉特伊斯兰组织活跃地区的反恐努力。根据<a href="https://www.economicsandpeace.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/GTI-2023-web.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">经济与和平研究所的数据，</a>去年萨赫勒地区的恐怖主义死亡人数占全球恐怖主义死亡人数的 43%，高于 2007 年的 1%。该智库表示，2022 年该地区发生的流血事件比南亚、中东和北非的总和还多。</p><p>尼日尔为地区安全发挥了建设性作用。约有 1,100 名美军和多达约 1,500 名法国士兵在那里作战。阿加德兹耗资 1.1 亿美元的美国无人机基地是撒哈拉以北地区（包括利比亚和阿尔及利亚）的重要作战前哨基地。现在这一切都面临着风险。</p><p>另一个风险是移民。在欧洲的支持下，尼日尔打击了人口走私，并帮助阻止了撒哈拉以南非洲移民向北流动。未遂政变危及了这种合作。尼日利亚、突尼斯、阿尔及利亚和利比亚正在与失业作斗争，来自尼日尔和撒哈拉以南非洲的工作年龄移民的激增可能成为稳定的另一个威胁。</p><p>自 2020 年以来，萨赫勒地区或与萨赫勒地区接壤的其他五个国家也发生了政变，如果尼日尔屈服，这条带将从大西洋延伸到红海。美国法律第 7008 条的一项规定会触发终止对军事政变推翻民主政府的国家的援助，尽管拜登政府在执行方面拥有自由裁量权。</p><p>欧盟已暂停安全合作和财政支持，国务卿安东尼·布林肯周六<a href="https://www.state.gov/secretary-antony-j-blinken-secretary-of-defense-lloyd-j-austin-iii-australian-deputy-prime-minister-and-minister-for-defense-richard-marles-and-australian-foreign-minister-penny-wong-at-a-joint-pr/" target="_blank" class="icon none">表示</a>，“我们与尼日尔的经济和安全伙伴关系——价值数亿美元，意义重大——取决于民主治理和宪法秩序的延续”这已经被打乱了。”然而西方还必须考虑拒绝美国的支持是否会造成俄罗斯和中国填补的真空。</p><p>马里去年驱逐了法国军队，并欢迎了瓦格纳集团的雇佣军。瓦格纳创始人叶夫根尼·普里戈任 (Yevgeny Prigozhin) 现在正在为尼日尔的收购尝试欢呼。政变领导人萨利福·莫迪将军本周访问了马里，并会见了马里国防部长，后者因与瓦格纳的关系而受到美国制裁。</p><p>周日，在首都尼亚美，数千名政变支持者在法国大使馆外抗议，要求法国退出，一些人挥舞着俄罗斯国旗。中国一直在扩大在非洲的投资和军事基础设施，尼日尔是世界第七大铀生产国。</p><p>周日，区域政治和经济联盟西非国家经济共同体（Ecowas）表示，除非政变策划者在一周内退缩，否则将采取“一切必要措施恢复尼日尔共和国的宪法秩序”。这可能包括武力。美国国务院周二表示，美国支持“西非经共体和该地区领导人为解决这一局势、恢复民主总统、尼日尔民选总统所做的努力”。</p><p>目前还不清楚西非经共体能否执行其最后通牒，如果失败将损害一个重要区域机构的信誉。马里和布基纳法索周一表示，他们将西非经共体对尼日尔的干预视为“宣战”，这增加了地区冲突的风险。</p><p>我们希望巴祖姆先生能够安然度过这一威胁，但他对尼日尔的控制已被削弱。这是非洲的又一糟糕事态发展，需要西方更多关注，以避免进一步的人员和战略损失。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:47:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-sahel-africa-mohamed-bazoum-state-department-c627cbc5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-sahel-africa-mohamed-bazoum-state-department-c627cbc5<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济与和平研究所</category><category>美国国务院</category><category>穆罕默德·巴祖姆</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Devon Archer’s Full Biden Story]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>副总统拜登将家族企业与他的乌克兰外交混在一起。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128331712341918"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128331712341918"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 6:47 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/devon-archer-testimony-transcript-house-oversight-hunter-biden-joe-biden-ukraine-a21915bc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829620?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 31 日，德文·阿彻 (Devon Archer) 在众议院监督委员会作证后离开奥尼尔众议院办公楼。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Chip Somodevilla/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周一，德文·阿彻 (Devon Archer) 与众议院监督委员会的闭门会议结束后，纽约的丹尼尔·戈德曼 (Daniel Goldman) 出现，对民主党进行了阐述：拜登总统与其儿子的商业伙伴的对话只是关于天气或其他细节的天真讨论。周四，当委员会公开完整的记录时，这一说法被揭露为虚假的。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>阿彻先生是亨特·拜登的前商业伙伴，并与他一起在乌克兰能源巨头布里斯马公司的董事会任职。阿彻先生将亨特给公司带来的附加值描述为“品牌”，也就是拜登的名字。当亨特让他的父亲通过免提与他的商业客户通话时，“有一个品牌正在传递。”</p><p>他进一步澄清说，正是乔·拜登“为该品牌带来了最大的价值”。换句话说，亨特正在出卖他父亲在华盛顿的权力。这就是Burisma 所付出的代价，而且看起来它的钱花得值。 “如果没有这个品牌，Burisma 就会倒闭，”阿切尔先生说。</p><p>乔·拜登在 2015 年 12 月访问基辅期间曾吹嘘自己利用 10 亿美元的美国援助解雇乌克兰检察官维克托·肖金。阿彻先生说，正在调查布里斯马的肖金先生“并没有特别在我的关注范围内”，而且他还被编造了一个关于肖金先生实际上“对布里斯马有好处”的故事。但他也表示，当亨特、Burisma 老板 Mykola Zlochevsky 和 ​​Burisma 执行官 Vadym Pozharski 在迪拜开会讨论华盛顿如何减轻他们的压力后“打电话给华盛顿”时，他并没有与他们通电话。</p><p>所有这些都凸显了乔·拜登将儿子的生意与副总统的职责混在一起的可怕判断力。拜登是奥巴马政府在乌克兰问题上的关键人物，乌克兰正在与俄罗斯的第一次入侵作战，他不能声称对儿子的交易一无所知。</p><p>奥巴马政府高级能源官员阿莫斯·霍赫斯坦 (Amos Hochstein) 2015 年警告副总统，俄罗斯支持的媒体正在利用亨特在 Burisma 董事会的存在来“破坏”美国的反腐败信息。第二年，驻基辅的高级外交官乔治·肯特在向国务院发出的信息中更加直言不讳。</p><p>肯特先生说：“乌克兰人听到了我们发来的一条信息，然后看到了另一组行为，该家族与一位已知的腐败人物有联系，而该人物的公司因不遵守石油/天然气行业的规则而闻名。”</p><p>阿彻先生还解释了亨特如何从哈萨克斯坦寡头凯内斯·拉基舍夫 (Kenes Rakishev) 那里收到 142,300 美元来购买一辆“昂贵的汽车”——菲斯克或保时捷。拉基舍夫先生与副总统及其儿子一起参加了 2014 年春季在华盛顿米兰咖啡馆举行的商务晚宴。莫斯科市长的妻子埃琳娜·巴图琳娜 (Elena Baturina) 也出席了会议，她向与阿切尔先生有关联的一家公司汇了 350 万美元。众议院委员会表示，将在发布下一批相关财务文件时提供更多细节。</p><p>当公众第一次得知亨特的肮脏交易时，乔·拜登否认曾与他讨论过儿子的生意。但阿彻先生还公布了拜登先生的一封信（在副总统官方文具上），信中称他对阿彻先生与他的儿子做生意感到多么“高兴”。这封信是在他和阿切尔先生与来访的中国国家主席胡锦涛共进午餐后写的。</p><p></p><h4> ***</h4><p>在办公室发展关系并在以后转化为商业机会是一回事，就像唐纳德·特朗普的女婿贾里德·库什纳在中东所做的那样。在任职期间利用办公室来推动家族企业是另一回事。正如阿彻先生所说，拜登品牌的优势在于，从法律上讲，“人们会被吓到去惹他们”。</p><p>无论乔·拜登是否从这些交易中拿走一分钱，这都是一种政治腐败。 2020 年，这将被媒体掩盖，但到 2024 年，这将成为一个问题。民主党人应该担心，随着更多关于拜登政商结合的事实浮出水面，这可能会帮助特朗普消除他的许多法律漏洞。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:47:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/devon-archer-testimony-transcript-house-oversight-hunter-biden-joe-biden-ukraine-a21915bc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/devon-archer-testimony-transcript-house-oversight-hunter-biden-joe-biden-ukraine-a21915bc<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>德文郡弓箭手</category><category>乔·拜登</category><category>亨特·拜登</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Democrats and the Trump Indictment Spectacle]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>他们希望选举始终以前总统为中心。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590128632785676328"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590128632785676328"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 6:46（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-democrats-arraignment-2024-election-fd490e8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829619?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 8 月 3 日，前总统唐纳德·特朗普在弗吉尼亚州阿灵顿罗纳德·里根华盛顿国家机场步行接受记者采访。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历克斯·布兰登/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周四，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>在华盛顿特区的联邦法院表示无罪，全世界的镜头都集中在前总统和现任候选人在被告席上的场面上。该法律案件将在未来几个月内审理，但要记住的政治要点是，这正是民主党希望选民关注的焦点：整天、每一天都在关注特朗普。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>媒体越是关注特朗普的法庭闹剧，公众就越不会关注拜登总统能力的下降或拜登推动家族企业的事实。 （见附近。）起诉书将所有人的注意力集中在特朗普的麻烦上，而不是拜登的记录或有关未来四年的辩论。</p><p>特朗普受审也意味着他的共和党总统提名竞争对手几乎无法引起媒体关注。媒体首先询问他们对特朗普的起诉有何看法，然后如果他们批评得不够充分，就会斥责他们。他们的政策，或者与特朗普先生的分歧，还不如在森林里喊叫。克里斯·克里斯蒂是特朗普最直言不讳的批评者，除了他对特朗普的评价之外，其他人都忽视了他。</p><p>所有这一切都让民主党人欣喜若狂，因为他们希望特朗普成为共和党候选人。他们希望共和党选民通过提名特朗普先生来回应这些指控，作为一种政治报复。不管这本质上意味着共和党将让民主党选择他们的提名人。</p><p>因此，我们在没有明显出口的情况下，倾向于 2024 年的竞选辩论，讨论现任总统的年龄和家族企业，以及前总统在 2020 年试图避免入狱时所做的事情。提一个奇怪的想法：这对国家不利。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-democrats-arraignment-2024-election-fd490e8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-democrats-arraignment-2024-election-fd490e8<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Republicans Return to the SALT Mines]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>八名议员希望补贴民主党州的高税收。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126124155460614"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126124155460614"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 6:39 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-republicans-tax-bill-salt-tax-gop-congress-d4b6bc6f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827981?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：安娜·钱梅梅克/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>众议院共和党的微弱多数保证了经常发生的戏剧性事件，最新的一集有一些议员支持民主党的税收政策。来自高税收州的一个团体希望提高州税和地方税的扣除额，他们正在搁置共和党的税收法案来实现这一目标。</p><p>至少八名议员正在采取措施增加可从联邦税单中扣除的州税和地方税金额。如果他们成功了，他们将撤销来之不易的共和党政策。共和党人在 2017 年税制改革中将这一被称为 SALT 的冲销上限限制在 10,000 美元。税收联合委员会估计，这一上限每年使联邦收入增加约 800 亿美元，这有助于抵消企业和个人较低的税率。</p><p>来自高税收州的立法者表示，对于他们的选民来说，这一上限是一项糟糕的协议。 “国会在 SALT 问题上搞砸了纽约人，”该组织领导人之一、众议员尼克·拉洛塔 (Nick LaLota) 7 月表示。 “我不会成为另一次国会试图搞砸纽约的人。”</p><p>与他一起参加的还有纽约州众议员安东尼·德斯波西托、马克·莫利纳罗、迈克·劳勒和安德鲁·加巴里诺，以及新泽西州的汤姆·基恩和克里斯·史密斯，以及加利福尼亚州的迈克·加西亚。据国会山消息人士透露，所有人都表示，他们将投票反对已通过筹款委员会的待决减税方案，除非对其进行修改以增加或取消 SALT 上限。这超过了共和党在预期的党派路线投票中可以承受的失去的五票。</p><p>但缺乏特殊恩惠是如何“搞砸”纽约的呢？州税率由奥尔巴尼等州首府确定，州政客可以自由降低税率。 SALT 扣除可以更容易地保持高税收，因为冲销可以保护居民免受这些惩罚性税率的痛苦。</p><p>由于蓝州税收是对高收入者征收的，因此扣除的好处大部分流向了最富有的纳税人。布鲁金斯学会 2020 年的一项分析发现，收入最高的 1% 的人将从取消 SALT 上限中获得 57% 的收益。</p><p>筹款委员会主席杰森·史密斯（Jason Smith）在 SALT 问题上没有做出让步，并表示他不希望密苏里州选民补贴进步海岸的税收优惠。他在政治上和税收政策优点上都是正确的。取消 SALT 将增加提高联邦税率以弥补收入损失的政治压力。</p><p>即使没有 SALT 行李，筹款计划也很平庸。它确实延长了 2017 年税改法案中即将到期的条款，但也包含了对标准扣除额的误导性提升。仅在两年内，未逐项列出的申报人的一般冲销额将增加 4,000 美元，使联合申报人的总金额达到约 32,000 美元。</p><p>对于收入超过 40 万美元的纳税人来说，奖金会更少，完全减少到 48 万美元左右。与降低所得税税率不同，这种短暂而有限的退税对纳税人增加工作或投资几乎没有什么激励作用。限制收入标准扣除额也是民主党将扩大的一个糟糕的税收先例。</p><p>众议院共和党领导人在与拜登总统达成六月债务上限协议后不久宣布了他们的税收计划，希望这能让选民更多地了解他们的财政优先事项。议长凯文·麦卡锡(Kevin McCarthy)原本寻求在国会8月休会前就该方案进行投票，但SALT僵局已将其最早推迟到9月。</p><p>这场斗争显示了众议院多数派在税收问题上的不团结，而税收问题曾经是共和党的优势。关于特别税收豁免的分歧正中民主党的下怀。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-republicans-tax-bill-salt-tax-gop-congress-d4b6bc6f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-republicans-tax-bill-salt-tax-gop-congress-d4b6bc6f<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>非金属矿开采/采石</category><category>基本材料/资源</category><category>采矿/采石</category><category>盐提取</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算/税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>众议院共和党</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算</category><category>税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>非金属矿开采</category><category>采石</category><category>基础材料</category><category>资源</category><category>矿业</category><category>盐提取</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Of Making Many Books There Is No End]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>决定哪些属于犹太人的架子肯定会导致肉体的厌倦。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590093933638186148"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11277182998813654381604590093933638186148"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">艾略特·考夫曼</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 6:33 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-making-many-books-there-is-no-end-3d8ff0b3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829587?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">考夫曼家族的非小说类书柜。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：埃利奥特·考夫曼</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>是什么让一本书成为犹太教的？当我和妻子合并我们的收藏时，我一直被这个问题困扰。我们留出一个书柜放小说，两个书柜放<em>《seforim》</em> ，装订精美的法典、塔木德卷和精选评论，知识渊博的观察者可以通过这些书准确地识别我们是什么样的犹太人。最后，我们专门用两个大书柜来存放非小说类书籍，分为犹太人和非犹太人。这就是麻烦所在。</p><p>这要归咎于罗伯特·O·帕克斯顿 (Robert O. Paxton) 1972 年的经典作品《维希法国》(Vichy France)。这位美国历史学家戳破了菲利普·贝当元帅对纳粹“被动抵抗”的神话，贝当元帅于 1944 年 8 月对法国人说：“如果我不能成为你们的剑，我会尝试成为你们的盾牌。”这甚至比他自己的行为更能原谅他们的行为。帕克斯顿揭露了该政权“寻求合作”，这种做法“得到了群众支持和精英参与”，并强调“维希在没有德国压力的情况下所做的所有事情，以及维希恳求和恳求德国人做的所有事情”。</p><p>当我的妻子反对将这本书放在我们的犹太非小说书架上时，我感到震惊。我结结巴巴地说，维希政府合作的记录当然与犹太人有关。但当她温和地指示我们“让法国人远离犹太人”时，我无法争辩。</p><p>接下来是新保守派。我希望犹太人的书架上有内森·格雷泽的社会学著作。他 1963 年与丹尼尔·帕特里克·莫伊尼汉 (Daniel Patrick Moynihan) 合作的《超越大熔炉》(Beyond the Melting Pot) 是 1970 年的精彩第二版，用很多话来为没有看到 60 年代的到来而道歉。它还包括直率的观察，例如，“犹太人已经更加意识到保守的工人阶级和中产阶级价值观的美德，他们一直践行但拒绝庆祝”，以及古怪的观察，例如，“异族通婚，融合的一个重要标志，在犹太人中仍然很低。”</p><p>我妻子意识到，问题在于这本书还涵盖了爱尔兰人、意大利人和纽约市的其他人种。它真的适合放在犹太人书架上与内厄姆·N·格拉泽 (Nahum N. Glatzer) 的《弗兰茨·罗森茨威格》(Franz Rosenzweig) 并列吗？撇开可疑的相似名字不谈，格雷泽对于我们狭隘的人民来说太宽泛了。我不得不克制自己不要争论所有现代社会科学本质上都是犹太教的。</p><p>在塞缪尔·戈德曼的“基督教犹太复国主义”问题上失败了两次，然后是第三次（我：“这是<em>犹太复国主义</em>！”；她：“这是<em>基督教</em>！”），我做了明智的事情：改变立场并继续争论。</p><p>我突然想到，莱昂·卡斯的《智慧的开端》在我们的犹太书柜上没有位置。在这部深受我们双方喜爱的作品中，这位芝加哥大学教授规定，他将以“与我阅读柏拉图《理想国》相同的精神”来阅读《创世记》——没有“预设和中介”，无论是犹太人的还是其他的。我嘲笑道，让我们相信他的话吧。他的评论不是犹太人的。</p><p>在我妻子的沮丧中，我看到了整个企业的危险。我是谁，可以从犹太传统中写出这样一本由犹太人转向犹太文本寻求智慧的书？</p><p>就好像我一直在误解现代正统犹太教的口号《托拉·乌马达》（ <em>Torah U&#39;Madda）</em> ，或者《托拉与世俗学习》，它的含义并不比莱尼·布鲁斯（Lenny Bruce）的“犹太人和非犹太人”更深，其中世界被整齐地一分为二。 “雷·查尔斯是犹太人。埃迪·坎托（Eddie Cantor）很俗气。布奈布里斯</p>是非犹太人的；哈达萨，犹太人，”布鲁斯开玩笑说。 “黑面包是犹太人的，而且，如你所知，白面包非常非犹太人。 。 。 。所有意大利人都是犹太人。希腊人很俗气——糟糕的酱汁。”<p></p><p>我们的犹太纪实书柜上的配对是按字母顺序排列的产物，但事实并非如此。他们没有赞扬和诋毁，而是欢欣鼓舞和同情，始终尊重犹太人的广泛经验。乔恩·利文森 (Jon Levenson) 的《上帝的爱：神圣的礼物、人类的感恩和犹太教中的相互忠诚》(The Love of God: Heavenly Gifts, Human Gratitude, and Mutual Faithiness in Judaism) 与普里莫·利维 (Primo Levi) 的《淹死者与得救者》(The Dried and the Saved) 已准备就绪，对于普里莫·利维 (Primo Levi) 来说，奥斯维辛是对我们造物主的最终定论。苏联拒绝者纳坦·夏兰斯基 (Natan Sharansky) 的回忆录《无惧邪恶》(Fear No Evil) 讲述了他为进入以色列而与克格勃 (KGB) 进行的斗争，当它与马尔卡·西姆科维奇 (Malka Simkovich) 的《发现第二圣殿文学》相遇时，它似乎取得了更大的胜利。</p><p>犹太故事是从我们粗略的分类体系中迸发出来的。犹太书架上的每一本书似乎都会引导我去读另一本关于非犹太书的书，然后再读第三本，通常是犹太作家写的，这两种书都可以。我们的卡夫卡日记本怎么样？正如《审判》一书的作者 1912 年在布拉格犹太市政厅对同化的德语文人所说的那样：“女士们先生们，你们对意第绪语的了解比你们想象的还要多。”</p><p>有些架子比其他架子更犹太化，但所有架子都在交谈。罗伯特·博克的《无精打采地走向蛾摩拉》可能听上去很俗气，而且它放在非犹太人的书柜上，但放在艾伦·布鲁姆的《美国思想的封闭》旁边，共鸣压倒了不和谐，甚至眨眼。</p><p>世俗的东西仍然必须与神圣的东西分开，我和我的妻子不想把洛里·考克斯·汉的帕特·布坎南的白宫备忘录放在旁边。</p>摩西·哈尔伯特尔的《纳赫曼尼德斯》。这两个书柜将保持分开，并再次与小说和<em>书柜</em>分开，但我热切希望从它们每个书柜中学到的知识能够在我们思想和婚姻的发展中相互融合。<p></p><p><em>考夫曼先生是《华尔街日报》的通讯编辑。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-making-many-books-there-is-no-end-3d8ff0b3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/of-making-many-books-there-is-no-end-3d8ff0b3<category>犹太教</category><category>塞福林</category><category>书柜</category><category>非小说类</category><category>小说</category><category>家庭</category><category>婚姻</category><category>犹太传统</category><category>纽约市</category><category>法国</category><category>纳粹德国</category><category>社会科学</category><category>圣经</category><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>宗教</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>宗教</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Unprecedented Jack Smith]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>如果像他在特朗普起诉书中提出的那样，撒谎的政客可以因“欺诈”而受到起诉，我们将需要很多新的监狱。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590128602129743516"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590128602129743516"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kimberley-a-strassel"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BS063_strass_AM_20180912122055.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kimberley-a-strassel" itemprop="url" rel="author">金伯利·斯特拉塞尔 (Kimberley A. Strassel)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 6:32 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-unprecedented-jack-smith-special-counsel-donald-trump-president-fraud-c076a2ee"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829527?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">特别顾问杰克·史密斯，8 月 1 日在华盛顿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：saul loeb/法新社/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>如果用一个词来形容每个人都希望华盛顿停止生产的东西，那就是“史无前例”。然而，我们又来了，特别检察官杰克·史密斯史无前例地指控一名政客参与“阴谋欺骗美国”。做好准备，迎接这个新的、具有惊人弹性的先例，以吸引许多其他人。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>这是史密斯先生最新猛烈抨击<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>的最大问题，除了其未经检验的法律理论和司法部双重标准的证据之外。正如前司法部长威廉·巴尔 (William Barr) 周三对 CNN 所说，“不提起诉讼是有原因的”，其中之一就是“将合法政治活动定为刑事犯罪的滑坡”。</p><p>将特朗普先生排除在外，并更广泛地考虑甚至《<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NYT" class="company-name">纽约时报》</a>所称的史密斯先生的“新颖方法”。史密斯先生承认，政客可以对公众撒谎。 Yet if that politician is advised by others that his comments are untruthful and nonetheless uses them to justify acts that undermine government “function,” he is guilty of a conspiracy to defraud the country. Dishonest politicians who act on dubious legal claims? There aren&#39;t enough prisons to hold them all.</p><p> Consider how many politicians might already be doing time had prosecutors applied this standard earlier. Both Al Gore and George W. Bush filed lawsuits in the 2000 election that contained bold if untested legal claims. Surely both candidates had advisers who told them privately that they may have legitimately lost—and neither publicly conceded an inch until the Supreme Court resolved the matter. Might an ultimate sore winner have used this approach to indict the loser for attempting to thwart the democratic process?</p><p> And why limit the theory to election claims? In 2014 the justices held unanimously that President Barack Obama had violated the Constitution by decreeing that the Senate was in recess so that he could install several appointees without confirmation. It was an outrageous move, one that Mr. Obama&#39;s legal counselors certainly warned was a loser, yet the White House vocally insisted the president had total “constitutional authority” to do it. Under Mr. Smith&#39;s standard, that was a <em>lie</em> that Mr. Obama used to <em>defraud</em> the public by jerry-rigging the function of a labor board with illegal appointments.</p><p> What&#39;s the betting someone told President Biden he didn&#39;t have the power to erase $430 billion in student loan debt. Oh, wait!这是正确的。 He told himself. “I don&#39;t think I have the authority to do it by signing with a pen,” he said in 2021. The House speaker advised him it was illegal: “People think that the president of the United States has the power for debt forgiveness. He does not,” <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/nancy-pelosi">Nancy Pelosi</a> said. Yet Mr. Biden later adopted the <em>lie</em> that he did, and took action to <em>defraud</em> taxpayers by obstructing the federal <em>function</em> of loan processing—until the Supreme Court made him stop. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> Read More Potomac Watch</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunters-sweetheart-plea-deal-justice-department-lawyer-tax-gun-charge-whistleblower-irs-e271d08f?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Hunter&#39;s Sweetheart Plea Deal</a> <span class="date">July 27, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-a-shame-about-wray-christopher-fbi-hearing-investigation-agents-washington-d54746d1?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">It&#39;s a Shame About Christopher Wray</a> <span class="date">July 13, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-bidens-smear-strategy-letter-shapley-justice-irs-laptop-whistleblower-7edb0c99?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Hunter Biden&#39;s Smear Strategy</a> <span class="date">July 6, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> If even a former president can be hit with conspiracy charges, what&#39;s to protect a mere congressman, or a failed candidate, or a consultant? For how long did Stacey Abrams falsely dispute her loss in the 2018 Georgia governor&#39;s race and pressure Georgia lawmakers to alter election procedures in ways that might undermine voting integrity on the basis of untruths? Would the advisers who egged her on in that pursuit qualify as co-conspirators, like the lawyers in Mr. Smith&#39;s indictment?</p><p> The press is rooting for the special counsel to go after Republican lawmakers who on the basis of Mr. Trump&#39;s claims objected to slates of electors on Jan. 6, 2021. Let&#39;s line them all up, including dozens of Democrats who objected to slates in 2001, 2005 and 2017—on the basis of <em>lies</em> and with the purpose of conspiring to obstruct (as the Smith indictment puts it) “the lawful federal government function by which the results of the presidential election are collected, counted, and certified.”</p><p> We now know that Rep. Adam Schiff looked at a classified surveillance warrant application against a Trump adviser, <em>lied</em> about its contents publicly, memorialized those lies in an official memo, and used it to help gin up an investigation that definitely impeded the <em>function</em> of the Trump administration. We have evidence that the Federal Bureau of Investigation officials behind that application—James Comey, Andrew McCabe, Peter Strzok—used a dossier full of <em>lies</em> to get that warrant. Fortunately for them, special counsel John Durham</p> chose not to take a flyer by indicting them for conspiracy.<p></p><p> Smith fans will say this is a special case, the “big” lie, a one-time necessity for justice. Yet once a bar is lowered, it will be lowered further. Remember when impeachments, special committees, the stripping of committee assignments, and contempt citations were rare? Of course future prosecutors will take this precedent and expand it in ever more novel ways.</p><p> There are any number of things as certain as death and taxes. One is that politicians will lie, and act on those untruths. Now that might make them felons.</p><p> <em>Write to kim@wsj.com.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-unprecedented-jack-smith-special-counsel-donald-trump-president-fraud-c076a2ee</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-unprecedented-jack-smith-special-counsel-donald-trump-president-fraud-c076a2ee<author><![CDATA[Kimberley A. Strassel]]></author><category> special counsel</category><category> defraud</category><category> doj</category><category>犯罪</category><category>politician</category><category> truth</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>classified</category><category>总统</category><category>选举</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Unclaimed Funds Brought My Father Back]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> His song royalties reminded me of his Glenn Miller-approved World War II ditty. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10194400307618314568704590014010538071940"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10194400307618314568704590014010538071940"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Michael Joseloff</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 6:31 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/unclaimed-funds-brought-my-father-back-arabella-war-record-label-2f023feb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829061?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Glenn Miller</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Redferns</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> I got word via email in February that New York state&#39;s unclaimed-funds office was holding money for me, a health-insurance check. I filled out the required paperwork and sent it off. Months went by. Puzzled by the delay, I revisited the funds website and was shocked when my late father&#39;s name, Stanley Joseloff, popped up. He too had unclaimed funds, from song royalties.</p><p> I knew that my father had moonlighted as a songwriter and had written the lyrics to “Dear Arabella,” which Glenn Miller&#39;s orchestra recorded in 1941. Again, I collected and mailed off the necessary paperwork. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="638" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829056?width=639&amp;height=638" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Uncredited</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> This was the second time since dad died in 1989 that Arabella and I had crossed paths. A decade ago, my wife and I were listening to WNYC when Danny Stiles, a broadcaster who billed himself as the “Vicar of Vintage Vinyl,” introduced “The Glenn Miller orchestra playing &#39;Dear Arabella,&#39; with lyrics by Stan Joseloff, music by Sidney Lippman. ” I was thrilled.</p><p> A World War II ditty, “Dear Arabella” tells of a draftee, Pvt. Johnny, who&#39;s writing to his girlfriend back home: “Dear Arabella, this Army life&#39;s OK / But Arabella I miss you more each day / . 。 。 Kindly remember wherever you may be / You&#39;re your private&#39;s private property.”</p><p> After my two Arabella encounters, I searched my father&#39;s old files and discovered more than 50 original songs and poems and a letter to his “Arabella” collaborator. Witty and rhyming, it was classic dad: “I could write a war song of bombs bursting in air, but who&#39;d be left to sing it by the rockets&#39; red glare?”</p><p> My father wanted to make songwriting his career, but his parents weren&#39;t keen on it. So after graduating from college and law school, he took a job as in-house counsel to Lee and JJ Shubert, the powerhouse theater producers and owners, which led to a 12-week gig in 1937 writing songs for “ Billy Rose&#39;s Aquacade.” Rose, an impresario and showman par excellence, staged his extravaganzas in an outdoor amphitheater with a large pool and cast of synchronized swimmers, actors and singers.</p><p> Dad&#39;s big break came when “Dear Arabella” won first prize in a Hearst Newspapers song contest. Glenn Miller chose it as his “Song of the Week,” and Hearst published the music and lyrics in 20 newspapers nationwide.</p><p> Few people outside the family have heard of the song today. But the unclaimed-funds notice and the play on the car radio brought my father back to me in a way nothing else could.</p><p> I&#39;m still waiting for the royalty check, not that I&#39;m going to cash it. I&#39;m going to frame it and place it alongside a treasured 78 rpm record with the trademark dog and phonograph RCA logo and the title “Dear Arabella” on the label.</p><p> <em>Mr. Joseloff is a television producer and author of “Chasing Heisenberg: The Race for the Atom Bomb.”</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/unclaimed-funds-brought-my-father-back-arabella-war-record-label-2f023feb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/unclaimed-funds-brought-my-father-back-arabella-war-record-label-2f023feb<category> dad</category><category> record</category><category> unclaimed fund</category><category> record label</category><category> arabella</category><category> new york</category><category> war</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>National/Public Security</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Music</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Risk News</category><category> Military Action</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category>艺术</category><category>entertainment</category><category>音乐</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>risk news</category><category> military action</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Talking Cure’ Review: The Joys of Spirited Conversation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> To chat with those who already agree with us can be comforting, but it proves no substitute for a real, revealing exchange of views. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590116490306890072"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829452?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Johnson, Boswell and company in conversation.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alamy Stock Photo </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590116490306890072"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Danny Heitman</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 6:29 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/talking-cure-review-the-joys-of-spirited-conversation-4567781c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> As we&#39;ve often been told, the art of conversation is on life support, ravaged by the excesses of technology. Hooked to our phones and laptops, or so the theory goes, we&#39;ve lost the true gift for gab. Sherry Turkle, one of many writers who have noted the problem, weighed in with her book “Reclaiming Conversation,” in 2015. “We hide from each other even as we&#39;re constantly connected to each other,” Ms. Turkle told readers. “For on our screens, we are tempted to present ourselves as we would like to be.”</p><p> In “Talking Cure,” billed as “an essay on the civilizing power of conversation,” Paula Marantz Cohen echoes some of Ms. Turkle&#39;s laments about online culture as a corrupting influence on conversation. But Ms. Cohen, a professor of English at Drexel University and the dean of its honors college, finds other culprits, too—some well-publicized, and others that readers might not have considered.</p><p> Political polarization quickly rears its head as a conversation killer, blocking the interchange of different perspectives that give a good talk its vitality. “To speak to the converted or the entirely familiar is not to truly converse,” Ms. Cohen writes. “It is to have one&#39;s beliefs reinforced; it is self-soothing but not self-developing.” Mentioning the liberal pedigree of her family, Ms. Cohen writes gratefully about how her world view was expanded by a deep friendship and decades of thoughtful exchanges with a conservative colleague who has since died. “What sustained us in our disagreement,” she recalls, “was our mutual respect, indeed deep affection, for each other. It was a feeling that carried moral as well as emotional weight.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/c3f4f045-936e-457a-a616-697f6cb3f8b8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Disagreement, Ms. Cohen suggests, is an essential element: “Good conversation digs deep into a subject, turns it over, examines it from angles that might otherwise remain in shadow, and presents hypotheses that may be wrong or even unpleasant, but thought-provoking.” Such openness to opposing viewpoints is now harder to come by in national life. “I used to routinely adopt the devil&#39;s advocate position in class,” she writes, “but I find it harder to do this now, when dissenting viewpoints are less tolerated and when playful or ironic positions are taken literally.”</p><p> As in many of her previous writings, such as “On Human Kindness,” a 2021 book that explored lessons from Shakespeare about empathy, in “Talking Cure” Ms. Cohen looks to literature for useful instruction about her subject. Though she makes numerous arguments for the civic benefits of conversation, the chief value of this book is its abiding reminder of the pleasure of good talk.</p><p> Ms. Cohen is deeply read, and her mind is like a curio cabinet that displays a collection of bright and interesting things.</p><p> In surveying centuries of celebrated talk—touching on figures as varied as Epictetus, William Wordsworth, Virginia Woolf and Langston Hughes—Ms. Cohen&#39;s book offers evidence that for all its challenges, conversation has been an impressively resilient fixture of our species. Her models of good conversation include Samuel Johnson, the 18th-century English wit whose bon mots were copiously recorded by his friend and biographer, James Boswell. But Ms. Cohen makes the point that Boswell was more than a mere stenographer of Johnson&#39;s dinner-table pronouncements. He was a cheerful interlocutor, challenging Johnson&#39;s assumptions in a way that brought out the best in his mentor. It&#39;s a lesson in how conversation can reveal our truest, fullest selves.</p><p> The obstacles to good conversation can be as simple as the spaces in which we&#39;d like to linger and chat. Ms. Cohen sighs at the popular fashion in industrial décor at restaurants, where steel tables and backless chairs don&#39;t exactly invite warm exchanges. More broadly, she finds that talk “of a staged and highly predictable sort” is all around us, “on talk shows, TV panels, interviews, YouTube clips and podcasts,” ersatz conversation that replaces the unpredictable, real thing with an often scripted substitute. One surprising figure she calls out for a negative effect on conversation is Ronald Reagan. His disciplined PR strategy, still a popular model, “flies in the face of the serendipity and spontaneity that characterize real conversation,” she writes. “It may well be that Reagan&#39;s example, through its extraordinary success and superficial appeal, debased political conversation—and beyond that, all conversation—more thoroughly than any other figure in history.”</p><p> One wouldn&#39;t even have to be a particular fan of Reagan to find Ms. Cohen&#39;s assertion a strange piece of hyperbole. (Later in “Talking Cure,” she points to more obvious enemies of conversation, dictators such as Hitler and Stalin.)</p><p> Ms. Cohen&#39;s glancing takedown of the 40th president doesn&#39;t reflect the general tone of “Talking Cure,” which is measured and magnanimous. Elsewhere, she mentions in a more salutary vein Reagan&#39;s convivial chats with his political opponent, House Speaker Tip O&#39;Neill. In a passage arguing that women&#39;s talk has often been unfairly dismissed as trivial, Ms. Cohen sympathetically cites former First Lady Nancy Reagan as a likely victim of sexism.</p><p> Maybe, as with the long-predicted demise of poetry, reading and the republic itself, the art of conversation just might pull through in spite of our folly. The poor state of good talk, after all, is an enduring complaint. Ms. Cohen quotes one commentator&#39;s fear that conversation, “so useful and innocent a pleasure, so fitted for every period and condition of life, and so much in all men&#39;s power, should be so much neglected and abused.”</p><p> That was Jonathan Swift, who left the scene in 1745.</p><p> <em>Mr. Heitman, a columnist for the Baton Rouge Advocate, frequently reviews books for the Journal.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 22:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/talking-cure-review-the-joys-of-spirited-conversation-4567781c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/talking-cure-review-the-joys-of-spirited-conversation-4567781c<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>Reviews</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>entertainment</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>reviews</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[BlackRock Gives Investors a Say]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> BlackRock clients who represent more than $550 billion in assets joined the Voting Choice program. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590124231422332908"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590124231422332908"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Salim Ramji</span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name">Joud Abdel Majeid</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 5:59 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blackrock-gives-investors-a-say-voting-proxy-choice-advisory-firm-57d9f403"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829071?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The floor of the New York Stock Exchange.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alamy Stock Photo</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The dog days of summer mark the end of proxy season, when most American corporations hold their annual meetings and shareholders vote on the election of directors, compensation and other corporate matters.</p><p> As more individual and institutional investors have turned from individual stocks to mutual and exchange-traded funds, the responsibility for voting at these annual meetings has been entrusted to fund managers like <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BLK" class="">BlackRock</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p><p> Many investors value having their asset managers handle proxy voting. Proxy statements can run more than 100 pages. For a person invested in 500 companies through an ETF or index fund, that could mean more than 1,000 hours of wading through materials to make informed decisions on thousands of proxy votes. Many of our clients trust our record as a fiduciary acting in their long-term financial interests.</p><p> Still, we believe in offering clients choices. Our firm has always used technology to give clients easier access to an array of investment options. Two years ago, we announced that we would begin providing choices for clients that want to participate more directly in proxy voting, starting with institutional ones like pension funds.</p><p> Today, all American public and corporate pension funds we serve can invest in products that let them vote the shares of the companies they own, easily and efficiently. Clients representing more than $550 billion in assets have enrolled in our Voting Choice program. This is a growing share of the $4.5 trillion of equity assets we manage in index funds. While the majority of our clients have asked us to continue voting proxies on their behalf, others are taking advantage of a growing set of options, including voting themselves. This strong client interest has catalyzed others in our industry to experiment with proxy-voting choices.</p><p> Last month, we took another step by announcing a plan for a pilot program that offers choices to individual investors in our largest exchange-traded fund. This plan—subject to approval by the board that governs our ETFs—would let millions of these individual investors select from different policies to decide how their share of the ETF will vote on the companies they own.</p><p> There are always critics. There is a myth that BlackRock blindly follows the recommendations of proxy advisory firms like Glass Lewis and Institutional Shareholder Services when voting on behalf of our clients. That myth is debunked if you look at the facts. Over the past 12 months, on shareholder proposals where ISS made a recommendation that was different from a company&#39;s management, BlackRock supported management 85% of the time and agreed with ISS only 15% of the time.</p><p> For BlackRock, it&#39;s about financial value, not social or political values. On proxy voting, our clients&#39; financial interests are paramount. BlackRock makes its decisions independently, informed by company disclosures, engagement with management, and proprietary and third-party research.</p><p> With Voting Choice, our clients choose from a menu of third-party voting policies or design their own policies. Since its launch, clients with about 30% of the assets enrolled in our program have chosen to use their own policies rather than those from third parties. Individual investors seldom sit at home writing their own proxy-voting policies, and many institutional investors prefer to choose from the third-party ones.</p><p> We now offer 14 different third-party voting policies—double the number offered when Voting Choice launched. These policies can be tailored to Catholic values, for union pension funds, or to policies that support environmental and social proposals. We also offer a governance-aligned policy that, rather than taking a view on environmental and social proposals, follows each corporate management team&#39;s recommendations. Yet, it focuses on commonly accepted principles of corporate governance and doesn&#39;t always support management on governance matters. This governance-aligned policy is the most popular third-party policy among our public pension fund clients in the US</p><p> Beyond the 14 policies we offer from the two largest proxy advisory firms, we are working to add policies from other firms. We have long argued that investors benefit from having more proxy advisory firms in the industry to choose from.</p><p> As we refine Voting Choice, our ambition is for all investors to have easy and efficient options to participate in proxy voting if they choose. Greater voting choice requires asset owners to invest time and resources in making informed decisions. But giving them a say strengthens shareholder democracy and supports America&#39;s capital markets, which improves people&#39;s lives here and around the world.</p><p> <em>Mr. Ramji is BlackRock&#39;s head of iShares and index investing. Ms. Abdel Majeid is BlackRock&#39;s global head of investment stewardship.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 21:59:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/blackrock-gives-investors-a-say-voting-proxy-choice-advisory-firm-57d9f403</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/blackrock-gives-investors-a-say-voting-proxy-choice-advisory-firm-57d9f403<category> proxy voting</category><category> proxy advisors</category><category> glass lewis</category><category> iss</category><category>养老金</category><category>voting choice</category><category> Financial Investment Services</category><category> Portfolio/Fund/Asset Management</category><category> Financial Services</category><category> Investing/Securities</category><category> Regulation/Government Policy</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>regulation</category><category> government policy</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category><category>financial investment services</category><category> portfolio</category><category> fund</category><category> asset management</category><category> financial services</category><category> investing</category><category> securities </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[How High Mortgage Rates Fuel Inflation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> It&#39;s costlier to move, so fewer houses are on the market. Less supply means higher prices and rents. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590124571052848674"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590124571052848674"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Tomas J. Philipson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 3, 2023 5:58 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-high-mortgage-rates-fuel-inflation-construction-sticky-fine-tune-3e40677d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828450?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An &#39;open house&#39; flag in Los Angeles, Sept. 22, 2022.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Allison Dinner/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Many Keynesian economists believe that government bureaucrats can fine-tune the economy with price controls in credit markets. The current housing market argues against that view. Interest-rate hikes may be raising rather than lowering core inflation.</p><p> As Keynesian logic goes, rate hikes should cut demand and thereby reduce inflation in markets that rely heavily on credit, such as housing and cars. Such industries contribute heavily to inflation measures—housing costs make up about 40% of the core consumer-price inflation. But housing costs are difficult to measure. Inflation indexes aim to measure the consumption cost of housing, captured by rents and, for homeowners, imputed rents.</p><p> The rate hikes since March 2022 may be raising rather than lowering measured housing costs by having unusual effects on supply and demand. Housing prices are trending upward this year, partially because rate hikes suppress the supply of housing as well as the demand. Some 40% fewer existing homes are for sale than before the pandemic. That&#39;s because about 90% of outstanding mortgages are financed at fixed low rates. No wonder owners don&#39;t want to sell.</p><p> When rate hikes lower supply more than demand, it raises rather than lowers housing prices. Meantime, as higher prices and financing costs deter would-be home buyers, rental demand and prices have increased as well. As a result, rate hikes may be inflationary rather than deflationary for 40% of core CPI.</p><p> Existing homes typically make up about 90% of new home sales, the rest being new construction. The Case-Shiller housing price index is focused on such existing homes and excludes new construction. Despite persistent rate hikes for close to a year and a half, this index is up during 2023. But because of the low inventory of existing homes, construction of new homes is booming. It accounts for 30% of home sales rather than the traditional share of about 10%. So rate hikes are fueling increased construction—another counterintuitive result.</p><p> For other credit-dependent industries such as cars, there are other pandemic-specific effects on prices, such as supply chains and chips. But the incremental effects from rate hikes are similar. Some 75% of car sales are for used cars and owners who are sitting on car loans at favorable rates. This reduces supply at the margin and contributes to the rise in used-car prices we have seen throughout 2023.</p><p> Given that housing prices are up for 2023, housing-cost inflation is forthcoming, as it is positively related to such prices with a lag. This suggests a continuation of sticky core inflation. But fighting it with more rate hikes may make it even stickier.</p><p> The reverse of these arguments is also true—rate cuts in 2024 could lower housing prices. When the mortgage penalty for selling gets cut, supply may come back more than demand. Housing construction could thus take a hit from future rate cuts.</p><p> Because the rate hikes were so rapid, credit-based industries such as housing and cars may not be as rate-sensitive, and may even operate in the opposite direction for a time. This adds to the general argument that well-intentioned bureaucrats can&#39;t easily forecast or fine-tune our unpredictable economy.</p><p> <em>Mr. Philipson, an economist at the University of Chicago, was a member of the White House Council of Economic Advisers, 2017-20, and its acting chairman, 2019-20.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 21:58:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-high-mortgage-rates-fuel-inflation-construction-sticky-fine-tune-3e40677d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-high-mortgage-rates-fuel-inflation-construction-sticky-fine-tune-3e40677d<category> housing</category><category> interest rates</category><category> rate hikes</category><category>供应</category><category>demand</category><category> mortage</category><category> consumer price index</category><category> Economic Performance/Indicators</category><category> Home Sales/Housing Affordability Figures</category><category> Monetary Policy</category><category> Interest Rates</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Housing Sales Figures</category><category> Housing Prices Figures</category><category> Real Estate Markets</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Mortgage Planning/Trends</category><category>个人财务</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>Money/Currency Markets</category><category> Money Markets</category><category> Commodity Markets</category><category> Energy Markets</category><category> Commodity/Financial Market News</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>economic performance</category><category> indicators</category><category> home sales</category><category> housing affordability figures</category><category> monetary policy</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>housing sales figures</category><category> housing prices figures</category><category> real estate markets</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>mortgage planning</category><category> trends</category><category>个人财务</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><ca